	url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123744487000026},
	abstract = {This chapter introduces the most commonly used method for computing value-at-risk (VaR), historical simulation, and discusses the pros and cons of this method. Historical simulation (HS) is widely used in practice because of two reasons: the ease with which it is implemented and its model-free nature. The HS technique is very easy to implement, there are no parameters that are to be estimated by maximum likelihood or any other method; therefore, no numerical optimization is performed. The HS technique is modelfree, as it does not rely on any particular parametric model such as a RiskMetrics model for variance and a normal distribution for the standardized returns. VaR is the most popular risk measure in use and HS is the most often used methodology to compute VaR.},
